cton, California","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/97298/acton-ca-93510/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/97298/acton-ca-93510/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"akron":{"description":"The average price of homes in Akron have increased over 14% this past year and the average rents have increased over 6%. More than 50% of the homes in Akron are occupied by renters, making it an ideal fit for rental property investors. Listed homes were on the market for a median of 31 days, down 41.9% from a year ago and the median sales price has increased by 6.4% year-over-year. Located in the heart of the city, the University of Akron enrolls researchers from around the world focusing on industries such as polymers, advanced materials, and engineering.","historical":[{"Appreciation":4.1,"Rent":2.6,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":7.4,"Rent":-5.4,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":8.8,"Rent":2.8,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":6.5,"Rent":3.2,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":14.2,"Rent":6.8,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"akron","name":"Akron, Ohio","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/akron-oh","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/akron-oh","text":"Historical rental returns taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/akron-oh/home-values/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/akron-oh/home-values/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"albany":{"description":"Albany is the capital city of New York State. The city is known for its architecture, commerce, culture, institutions of higher education, and rich history. It is the economic and cultural core of the Capital District of the State of New York. This property is located near Albany Medical Center, Times Union Center, Empire State Plaza, Lark Street, State Offices, and courts. It has easy access to local & regional bus routes and highways. New York plans to invest $1 billion to expand chip research in Albany. [Click here](https://www.nytimes.com/2023/12/11/technology/new-york-chips-act-albany.html) to learn more.","historical":[{"Appreciation":0.65,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":7.95,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":5.49,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":13.39,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":15.41,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":11.73,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":8.28,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"albany","name":"Albany, New York","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/62472/albany-ny-12202/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/62472/albany-ny-12202/","text":"Historical appreciation returns taken from"}]},"albuquerque":{"description":"Albuquerque, the largest city in New Mexico, is renowned for its rich cultural heritage, diverse population, and unique southwestern charm. Founded in 1706 as a Spanish colonial outpost, it sits in the high desert along the Rio Grande, offering a semi-arid climate with hot summers and mild winters. The city\'s cultural tapestry is woven from Native American, Hispanic, and Anglo influences, reflected in its festivals, architecture, and vibrant arts scene. Albuquerque\'s economy thrives on technology, healthcare, education, and tourism, with key institutions like the University of New Mexico and Sandia National Laboratories. Notable attractions include the historic Old Town, the annual Albuquerque International Balloon Fiesta, and the scenic Sandia Mountains, providing abundant opportunities for outdoor activities and exploration.","historical":[{"Appreciation":3.5,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":2,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":3.9,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":7.2,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":11,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":14.8,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":11,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":6.1,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"albuquerque","name":"Albuquerque, New Mexico","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/95317/albuquerque-nm-87123/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/95317/albuquerque-nm-87123/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"atlanta":{"description":"The Atlanta real estate market continues to thrive. Job growth, a growing population, and housing affordability make Atlanta an attractive market for investing in rental properties, especially when 50% of the households in the metro area rent rather than own. Atlanta is known for its low seasonality for short-term rentals and boasts an average daily rate of $178, an average occupancy rate of 53% and average monthly revenue of $2,136. Atlanta recently ranked as the #1 best city for techies by Livability.com, due to the city\'s massive growth in tech job offerings and the dozens of high-profile startups in the city.","historical":[{"Appreciation":9.12,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":10.22,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":9.68,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":2.68,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":3.91,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":17.5,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":5.74,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"atlanta","name":"Atlanta, Georgia","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/37211/atlanta-ga/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/37211/atlanta-ga/","text":"Historical appreciation returns taken from"}]},"atlantic_city":{"description":"Atlantic City, New Jersey, offers a vibrant mix of entertainment, natural beauty, and history. Known for its iconic boardwalk, the city features casinos, luxury hotels, and unique attractions like Steel Pier and the Absecon Lighthouse. Its beaches provide a relaxing escape, perfect for sunbathing, swimming, or fishing, while the nearby Atlantic County Parks System offers hiking and birdwatching opportunities. The city is a hub for nightlife and dining, hosting a variety of restaurants, bars, and clubs that cater to diverse tastes. Events and festivals, such as the Atlantic City Airshow and seafood festivals, draw large crowds, creating a lively year-round atmosphere. Its outlet shopping district, Tanger Outlets, attracts shoppers seeking brand-name goods at discounted prices, boosting the local economy. Cultural experiences abound with places like the Atlantic City Historical Museum and live performances at Boardwalk Hall, which has hosted everything from concerts to boxing matches. The city\'s resurgence efforts, including infrastructure upgrades and urban redevelopment, have made it increasingly appealing to tourists and residents alike.","historical":[{"Appreciation":-13.3,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":23.2,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":15.9,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":19.2,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":15.7,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":13.6,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":12.4,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":16,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"atlantic_city","name":"Atlantic City, New Jersey","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/61074/atlantic-city-nj-08401/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/61074/atlantic-city-nj-08401/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"austin":{"description":"Many individuals consider moving to Austin, Texas for its thriving economy, abundant job opportunities, and relatively lower cost of living compared to other tech hubs. Dubbed \'Silicon Hills\' for its burgeoning tech scene, Austin hosts major companies like Dell, IBM, Apple, and Google alongside numerous startups. Its high quality of life is underscored by a vibrant arts and culture scene, diverse culinary offerings, and plentiful outdoor recreational activities. Austin\'s progressive values, inclusive community, and renowned educational institutions, such as the University of Texas at Austin, further contribute to its appeal. With a mild climate and welcoming atmosphere, Austin continues to attract people from all backgrounds seeking a dynamic and fulfilling lifestyle.","historical":[{"Appreciation":6.22,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":3.48,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":1.57,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":2.73,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":11.85,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":45.71,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":0.07,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"austin","name":"Austin, Texas","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/92576/leander-tx-78641/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/92576/leander-tx-78641/","text":"Historical appreciation returns taken from"}]},"avon_park":{"description":"Avon Park, nestled in central Florida, is experiencing a resurgence in population and business activity. With a population of approximately 9,789, it offers a suburban atmosphere where residents predominantly own their homes. Families and retirees are drawn to its sparse suburban environment. The town boasts various outdoor and indoor recreational opportunities, along with a range of dining options from good to exceptional. Notable attractions include Maxwell Groves Country Store, South Florida State College Performing Arts Events, Highlands Ridge Golf Club - North Course, Avon Park Depot Museum, and SFSC Museum of Florida Art & Culture.","historical":[{"Appreciation":11.2,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":11.8,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":9.5,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":9,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":11.7,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":25.4,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":15.4,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"avon_park","name":"Avon Park, Florida","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/72840/avon-park-fl-33825/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/72840/avon-park-fl-33825/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"baltimore_maryland":{"description":"Baltimore, Maryland, offers a rich cultural heritage, vibrant neighborhoods, and an affordable cost of living compared to nearby cities like Washington, D.C. The city is known for its historic charm, waterfront attractions, and diverse dining scene. Residents enjoy access to parks, cultural institutions like the Walters Art Museum, and unique neighborhoods such as Federal Hill and Fells Point. Baltimore provides opportunities for real estate investing due to its relatively low property prices, growing rental demand, and revitalization efforts in many areas. Neighborhoods like Canton, Hampden, and Mount Vernon attract both renters and buyers. Investors often target rowhouses, multi-family units, and properties eligible for tax credits or renovation incentives. The city\'s Opportunity Zones and steady population growth make it appealing for long-term investment. However, thorough market research and understanding of local regulations are crucial for success.","historical":[{"Appreciation":5.6,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":10.7,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":22.8,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":12.7,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":18.8,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":14.8,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":3.2,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":5.6,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":2.5,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"baltimore_maryland","name":"Baltimore, Maryland","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/79767/shelby-mi-49455/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/79767/shelby-mi-49455/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"berkeley":{"description":"Berkeley is a city in Northern California on the east side of San Francisco Bay. It\'s home to the University of California, Berkeley, birthplace of the 1960s Free Speech Movement. Living in Berkeley offers residents an urban suburban mix feel and most residents rent their homes. Berkeley is famous for its bars, restaurants, coffee shops, and parks. The average rent price in Berkeley was $2,495 in September, 2023, and the housing market is very competitive. Homes in Berkeley receive 6 offers on average and sell in around 14 days.","historical":[{"Appreciation":4.54,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":12.84,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":1.85,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":4.48,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":6.41,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":11.22,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":-4.63,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"berkeley","name":"Berkeley, California","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/97836/berkeley-ca-94702/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/97836/berkeley-ca-94702/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"birmingham_alabama":{"description":"Often referred to as the cradle of the American Civil Rights Movement, Birmingham, Alabama was founded back in 1871, right after the Civil War. Today, Birmingham has transformed itself into a medical research, banking, and services hub. Located at the base of the Appalachian Mountains, the city has a vibrant downtown and world-class dining scene right in the middle of one of the country\'s most livable cities.  Birmingham housing prices continue to rise as more residents and businesses move to cities where the quality of life is strong and the cost of living is still affordable.  Birmingham is known for being one of the best cities in the U.S. for renters. Although rents are still on the rise, the city is still relatively affordable with a cost of living that\'s below the national average. Home prices in Birmingham have increased by over 93% over the last decade. Over just the last month alone, home prices have increased by 1.4%, while over the past 12 months home prices have increased by nearly 19%.","historical":[{"Appreciation":-0.38,"Rent":1.67,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":4.12,"Rent":5.29,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":6.7,"Rent":11.84,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":9.83,"Rent":-10.58,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":17.87,"Rent":21,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"birmingham_alabama","name":"Birmingham, Alabama","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/birmingham-al","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/birmingham-al","text":"Historical rental returns for 3 bedroom properties taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/10417/birmingham-al/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/10417/birmingham-al/","text":"Historical appreciation returns for Single Family Homes taken from"}]},"black_creek":{"description":"Black Creek, situated in the town of New Hudson within Allegany County, New York, USA, is characterized as a hamlet. Its name originates from a nearby stream. Positioned between Cuba and Belfast along Route 305, Black Creek is recognized for its substantial population of Amish residents.","id":"black_creek","name":"Black Creek, New York"},"black_hawk_colorado":{"description":"Black Hawk is one of Colorado\'s top destination cities both day and night. Here, you can explore Colorado\'s authentic past, enjoy outdoor activities like hiking, biking, & skiing, and experience world-class restaurants, casinos, and luxury stays. Vacation rentals are highly sought after in Black Hawk because of the ability to get high rental and occupancy rates both in the summer and the winter ski seasons. This lack of seasonality helps short-term rental properties in Black Hawk get higher-than-average nightly rates, with the average nightly rate being $596.","historical":[{"Appreciation":11.597,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":8.57,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":9.05,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":4.95,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":14.12,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":15.14,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":7.1,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"black_hawk_colorado","name":"Black Hawk, Colorado","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/93375/central-city-co-80422/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/93375/central-city-co-80422/","text":"Historical appreciation returns taken from"}]},"briarcliff_manor":{"description":"Briarcliff Manor offers a unique blend of small-town charm and upscale living in Westchester County. Nestled along the Hudson River and surrounded by lush greenery, it boasts scenic beauty and a peaceful atmosphere. The village is known for its excellent schools, safe neighborhoods, and strong sense of community. Residents enjoy access to outstanding parks like Law Memorial Park and Rockefeller State Park Preserve, ideal for hiking and outdoor activities. The downtown area features quaint shops, caf\xe9s, and restaurants that give the town its warm, welcoming character. Briarcliff also has convenient access to major highways and Metro-North, making it easy to reach New York City while enjoying suburban tranquility. Historic homes and well-maintained properties line its quiet streets, adding to its appeal. With its mix of natural beauty, top-tier amenities, and tight-knit feel, Briarcliff Manor is one of Westchester\'s most desirable places to live.","historical":[{"Appreciation":1,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":1.9,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":-2.6,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":4.7,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":9.4,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":8.9,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":7.5,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":6.7,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"briarcliff_manor","name":"Briarcliff Manor, New York","sources":[{"link":" https://www.zillow.com/home-values/61825/briarcliff-manor-ny-10510/","linkText":" https://www.zillow.com/home-values/61825/briarcliff-manor-ny-10510/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"charlotte":{"description":"Charlotte is consistently ranked as one of the hottest real estate markets in the U.S., thanks to its economic growth potential, diverse economy, and excellent quality of life. It is the most populated city in North Carolina and one of the fastest-growing metro areas in the country, attracting both people and businesses. Charlotte is the second largest financial center in the U.S., with seven Fortune 500 companies and a thriving job market that includes high-tech, white collar, and service and distribution jobs. It is also home to popular professional sports teams and has one of the best year-round climates in the country.","historical":[{"Appreciation":10.28,"Rent":4.68,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":10.6,"Rent":4.09,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":8.31,"Rent":7.27,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":6.22,"Rent":2.97,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":12.77,"Rent":8.46,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":23.12,"Rent":10.71,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":8.65,"Rent":8.55,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"charlotte","name":"Charlotte, North Carolina","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/charlotte-nc","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/charlotte-nc","text":"Historical rental returns for 3 bedroom properties taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/24043/charlotte-nc/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/24043/charlotte-nc/","text":"Historical appreciation returns for Single Family Homes taken from"}]},"chattanooga":{"description":"The city of Chattanooga is located along the Tennessee River, with a metropolitan area that includes northwest Georgia and northeast Alabama. The city is a transportation hub for the southeastern United States, and is less than 200 miles from major cities including Atlanta, Nashville, Knoxville, Huntsville, and Birmingham, Alabama. Chattanooga is a great market for rentals, with around 40% of the households currently being occupied by renters. The median rent for 3 bedroom homes in Chattanooga is $1,714.","historical":[{"Appreciation":8.63,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":9.09,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":5.72,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":8.42,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":11.18,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":19.27,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":8.32,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"chattanooga","name":"Chattanooga, Tennessee","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/37837/chattanooga-tn/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/37837/chattanooga-tn/","text":"Historical appreciation returns taken from"}]},"chicago":{"description":"Chicago is the third most populous U.S. city, has the third busiest airport, and is significantly more affordable than other tier one markets like New York or Los Angeles. The average price of homes in Chicago have increased over 7% this past year and the average rents have increased over 16% according to [Zumper](https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/chicago-il) and [Zillow](https://www.zillow.com/chicago-il/home-values/), respectively. Millennials and Gen Z make up 41% of the population in Chicago, and more than 39% of Chicagoans hold a bachelor\'s or advanced degree.\\n\\nThe median rent in Chicago is $2,250 per month for a 3 bedroom home, and renter-occupied households in Chicago make up 53% of the total occupied housing units in the city. This, alongside Chicago having an affordability index of 4 out of 10, helps explain the very high percentage of people renting in Chicago\u2013\u2013a great sign for any property investor.","historical":[{"Appreciation":6.93,"Rent":-39.43,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":5.26,"Rent":-16.79,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":2.31,"Rent":17.94,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":-0.38,"Rent":-6.95,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":7.14,"Rent":16.4,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"chicago","name":"Chicago, Illinois","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/chicago-il","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/chicago-il","text":"Historical rental returns for 3 bedroom properties taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/chicago-il/home-values","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/chicago-il/home-values","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"cincinnati":{"description":"In just this past year, Cincinnati has seen a 15% increase in property appreciation and almost an 11% increase in rents\u2013\u2013making it one of the best markets in the country for real estate investing. Single family homes sell faster in Cincinnati than in any other market besides Omaha, Nebraska and more than 50% of the homes in Cincinnati are rented\u2013\u2013which is one of the highest rates in the country. Cincinnati is not only the largest city in Ohio, but it is also home to three major league sports teams, and it has seen an increase in jobs in all employment sectors over the past two years.","historical":[{"Appreciation":7.38,"Rent":6.65,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":6.25,"Rent":6.82,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":9.41,"Rent":21.35,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":5.37,"Rent":-4.28,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":15.3,"Rent":10.99,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"cincinnati","name":"Cincinnati, Ohio","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/cincinnati-oh","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/cincinnati-oh","text":"Historical rental returns for 3 bedroom properties taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/cincinnati-oh/home-values/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/cincinnati-oh/home-values/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"cinnaminson":{"description":"Cinnaminson, New Jersey, offers a blend of suburban comfort and community charm, making it an appealing place to live. Its location provides easy access to Philadelphia, just 10 miles away, and major highways like Route 130 and I-295, making commuting convenient. The town boasts excellent schools, appealing to families seeking quality education. Residents enjoy a variety of recreational amenities, including parks, sports fields, and the Riverton Country Club for golf enthusiasts. Cinnaminson\'s small-town feel is complemented by a range of local businesses, restaurants, and shopping centers, ensuring convenience without sacrificing a sense of community. The township hosts events and activities year-round, fostering a close-knit environment. Safety and well-maintained neighborhoods add to its appeal. With a mix of affordability, accessibility, and family-friendly living, Cinnaminson balances modern conveniences with suburban tranquility, making it an ideal choice for those seeking a welcoming and vibrant place to call home.","id":"cinnaminson","name":"Cinnaminson, New Jersey"},"cleveland":{"description":"The average price of homes in Cleveland have increased over 18% this past year and the average rents have increased over 8%. More than 50% of the homes in Cleveland are occupied by renters, making it an ideal fit for rental property investors. Cleveland ranks among the top 10 U.S. cities for population growth of college-educated millennials according to the Cleveland Foundation\'s [in-depth study.](https://www.clevelandfoundation.org/news_items/millennial-residents/) \\n\\n Employment growth in Cleveland is 1.43% year-over-year, and the GDP of Cleveland has increased by more than 12% in the last decade. Forbes recently speculated that Cleveland might become the country\'s next technology hub. Biotechnology, fuel cell research, and technology are three of the fastest growing employment sectors.","historical":[{"Appreciation":9.02,"Rent":1.43,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":12.28,"Rent":-5.88,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":13.25,"Rent":12.5,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":6.47,"Rent":0,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":18.73,"Rent":8.89,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"cleveland","name":"Cleveland, Ohio","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/cleveland-oh","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/cleveland-oh","text":"Historical rental returns for 3 bedroom homes taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/cleveland-oh/home-values/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/cleveland-oh/home-values/","text":"Historical appreciation returns for single family homes taken from"}]},"dallas_fort_worth":{"description":"The population of the Dallas-Fort Worth area continues to grow exponentially, and it is now the 4th largest metro area in the country, up from 6th place in 2010. DFW was only one of three metros to gain at least 1.2 million residents since 2010, alongside Houston and NYC. Dallas-Fort Worth could see the biggest population surge in the country this decade, with the population projected to grow by nearly 18% by 2029. It is the nations #1 job market thanks to solid employment gains and migration of new residents from other cities. Employment growth in Dallas-Fort Worth is 5.6% year-over-year and median household incomes in DFW grew by over 4% year-over-year. Median property values also increased by more than 6% in just the past 12 months. DFW International Airport (DFW) is the 2nd largest airport in the U.S. and is bigger than the island of Manhattan. Days on market (median) for properties is 62 days with single-family homes in Dallas selling nearly 14% faster than a year ago. Renter-occupied households in Dallas account for 44% of the total occupied housing units in the metropolitan area.","historical":[{"Appreciation":11.53,"Rent":5.06,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":11.49,"Rent":2.28,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":7.21,"Rent":3.53,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":3.84,"Rent":1.64,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":8.33,"Rent":4.7,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"dallas_fort_worth","name":"Dallas-Fort Worth, Texas","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/fort-worth-tx","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/fort-worth-tx","text":"Historical rental returns for 4 bedroom properties taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/fort-worth-tx/home-values/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/fort-worth-tx/home-values/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"daytona_beach":{"description":"Daytona Beach, Florida has gained global recognition for its rich racing heritage, playing host to prestigious motorsports events such as the renowned Daytona 500, famously dubbed the \\"Great American Race.\\" Beyond its racing scene, the city boasts a vibrant array of arts, cultural landmarks, historical sites, shopping outlets, golf courses, and sporting extravaganzas. Notably, Daytona Beach is celebrated for its picturesque beaches, lively water parks, and vibrant arcades lining the boardwalk.","historical":[{"Appreciation":6.9,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":7.2,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":7.4,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":4.7,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":7.4,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":21.6,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":16.7,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"daytona_beach","name":"Daytona Beach, Florida","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/71797/daytona-beach-fl-32118/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/71797/daytona-beach-fl-32118/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"delray_beach":{"description":"Delray Beach, Florida, is a vibrant coastal town known for its stunning beaches, lively downtown, and relaxing tropical atmosphere. Whether you\'re seeking sun-soaked relaxation or exciting nightlife, this charming destination has something for everyone. The pristine shoreline offers soft sand and clear blue waters, perfect for swimming, paddleboarding, or simply enjoying a sunset stroll. Just a short ride away, Atlantic Avenue buzzes with energy, featuring a mix of upscale restaurants, cozy caf\xe9s, unique boutiques, and a thriving arts scene. Delray Beach\'s welcoming community and free local transportation make it easy to explore without hassle. Outdoor enthusiasts can enjoy lush parks, golf courses, and water activities, while culture lovers can visit museums and galleries showcasing local talent. With its perfect blend of leisure and entertainment, Delray Beach delivers an unforgettable escape, where relaxation meets adventure in an elegant, sun-drenched paradise.","historical":[{"Appreciation":6.9,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":6.6,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":5.2,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":9.6,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":26,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":20.1,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":7,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":-0.2,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"delray_beach","name":"Delray Beach, Florida","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/72610/delray-beach-fl-33444/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/72610/delray-beach-fl-33444/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"denver":{"description":"Denver, known as the \\"Mile High City\\" for its elevation of 5,280 feet, offers a unique blend of urban sophistication and natural beauty. Its proximity to the Rocky Mountains provides residents with year-round outdoor activities, from hiking and biking to skiing. The city\'s cultural scene is vibrant, featuring institutions like the Denver Art Museum and a dynamic culinary landscape with diverse restaurants and breweries. Economically, Denver thrives with industries such as technology and energy, contributing to a robust job market. The city boasts a strong sense of community, with numerous festivals, farmers\' markets, and neighborhood events fostering connections among residents. Additionally, Denver\'s extensive public transportation system and bike-friendly infrastructure make commuting convenient and environmentally friendly. The city\'s commitment to sustainability is evident in its numerous parks and green spaces, promoting a healthy and active lifestyle.","historical":[{"Appreciation":5.4,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":12.4,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":8.4,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":5.8,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":8.9,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":13.5,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":5,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":0.7,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"denver","name":"Denver, Colorado","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/96757/twentynine-palms-ca-92252/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/96757/twentynine-palms-ca-92252/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"detroit":{"description":"The average price of homes in Detroit have increased over 25% this past year and the average rents have increased over 12%. Detroit is the headquarters of 100 of the Fortune 500 companies including Walmart and Penske. High-end retailers like Whole Foods have been opening up new stores at a rapid pace over the past two years and big tech companies like Microsoft, Google, and Pinterest have recently opened new offices in The Motor City.\\n\\n Detroit has seen the highest growth of millennials moving in over the last decade according to the [Detroit Chamber](https://www.detroitchamber.com/sor/)\u2013\u2013 and Millennials and Generation Z make up 38% of the population. Forbes ranks Detroit as one of the best places for business and careers in the U.S., with the city being home to an increasing number of companies in emerging technologies such as nanotechnology and hydrogen fuel cell development. Employment growth in Detroit is 1.77% year-over-year and the GDP has increased by over 28% in the last decade.","historical":[{"Appreciation":25.76,"Rent":2,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":12.04,"Rent":3.53,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":27,"Rent":1.01,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":4.14,"Rent":6.25,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":25.34,"Rent":12.35,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"detroit","name":"Detroit, Michigan","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/detroit-mi","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/detroit-mi","text":"Historical rental returns for 3 bedroom homes taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/detroit-mi/home-values/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/detroit-mi/home-values/","text":"Historical appreciation returns for single family homes taken from"}]},"dunedin":{"description":"Just 30 minutes west of Tampa on Florida\'s Gulf Coast, Dunedin is home to unspoiled islands, white-sand beaches, miles of trails, and a lively, bike-friendly downtown of quaint shops, craft breweries, and independent eateries. Visitors can explore Dunedin\'s outdoors in a variety of ways. Dunedin is known for Honeymoon Island which is linked to the mainland by Dunedin Causeway, offering views over St. Joseph Sound. Downtown, Hammock Park is home to owls, woodpeckers and a butterfly garden. The Fred Marquis Pinellas Trail runs through the city.","historical":[{"Appreciation":10.84,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":12,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":7.9,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":7.64,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":11.86,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":27.72,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":8,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"dunedin","name":"Dunedin, Florida","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/73181/dunedin-fl-34698/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/73181/dunedin-fl-34698/","text":"Historical appreciation returns taken from"}]},"everett":{"description":"Everett, Washington offers a vibrant mix of natural beauty, economic opportunity, and small-town charm just 30 minutes north of Seattle. Located on the shores of Port Gardner Bay, it\'s a haven for outdoor lovers\u2014with waterfront parks, marinas, and stunning views of the Olympic Mountains. The historic downtown is full of local shops, breweries, and restaurants, while the Everett Marina is one of the largest on the West Coast. Boeing\'s massive production facility anchors the local economy and draws aviation enthusiasts from around the world. Families enjoy top-rated schools, community events, and easy access to both the Cascades and Puget Sound. With a growing arts scene, proximity to tech and aerospace jobs, and a more relaxed pace than the big city, Everett blends the best of Pacific Northwest living with affordability and convenience. It\'s an ideal spot for both young professionals and families seeking space without sacrificing opportunity.","id":"everett","name":"Everett, Washington"},"fallwood":{"description":"Columbia, Missouri, is a vibrant city known for its college-town charm, outdoor beauty, and cultural attractions. Home to the University of Missouri, Columbia College, and Stephens College, it thrives with a youthful energy, lively arts scene, and exciting sports events. The downtown area, known as The District, offers unique shops, local restaurants, and entertainment venues, making it a hub of activity. Nature lovers enjoy Rock Bridge Memorial State Park, featuring scenic trails, caves, and the famous Devil\'s Icebox. The MKT Trail, a popular biking and walking path, connects to the larger Katy Trail, offering picturesque views of Missouri\'s countryside. Each fall, the Roots N Blues Festival draws music lovers, while the True/False Film Festival brings international filmmakers and cinephiles together. With its combination of academic excellence, outdoor recreation, and cultural experiences, Columbia stands out as one of Missouri\'s most dynamic and welcoming cities.","historical":[{"Appreciation":3.3,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":1,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":5,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":9,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":14,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":9.7,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":2.7,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":5,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"fallwood","name":"Fallwood, Missouri","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/86717/columbia-mo-65203/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/86717/columbia-mo-65203/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"gatlinburg":{"description":"Pigeon Forge, Tennessee, nestled in the Smoky Mountains, is a vibrant destination known for its mix of natural beauty and family-friendly attractions. One of its biggest draws is Dollywood, a world-class theme park offering thrilling rides, live music, and Appalachian culture. The nearby Great Smoky Mountains National Park provides endless outdoor adventures like hiking, scenic drives, and wildlife viewing. The Island in Pigeon Forge is another popular spot, featuring shopping, dining, and the iconic Great Smoky Mountain Wheel. For a taste of Southern charm, visitors enjoy dinner shows like Dolly Parton\'s Stampede and Pirates Voyage. The area also boasts unique museums, including the Titanic Museum and Alcatraz East. Whether you\'re seeking adventure, entertainment, or relaxation, Pigeon Forge combines rustic charm with modern fun, making it a top vacation choice for families, couples, and nature lovers alike.","id":"gatlinburg","name":"Gatlinburg, Tennessee"},"gibsonburg":{"description":"Gibsonburg, Ohio offers a peaceful small-town charm with a strong sense of community. Residents enjoy the slower pace of life, where neighbors know each other and local events bring people together. The town is surrounded by beautiful natural scenery, including the nearby Gibsonburg Quarry and Williams Park, which offer walking trails, fishing, and outdoor activities for all ages. Gibsonburg is also known for its excellent schools and safe neighborhoods, making it a great place to raise a family. The cost of living is affordable, and the town is just a short drive from larger cities like Toledo and Fremont, offering access to urban amenities without sacrificing the tranquility of rural living. Local businesses and eateries add to the town\'s charm, and there\'s a pride in preserving Gibsonburg\'s history and traditions.","historical":[{"Appreciation":3.5,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":9.2,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":0.2,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":16.1,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":9.7,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":5.5,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":8.7,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":7.2,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"gibsonburg","name":"Gibsonburg, Ohio","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/76673/gibsonburg-oh-43431/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/76673/gibsonburg-oh-43431/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"huntsville_alabama":{"description":"Huntsville is the most populous city in Alabama and is located in the Tennessee River Valley in the northernmost part of the state. Huntsville has an annual job growth of 3.1% and an unemployment rate of just 1.6%. Home values in Huntsville increased by 30% over the past year,  and there is less than a 1 month supply of homes on the market, indicating a housing market that strongly favors sellers. Demand for real estate and rental property in Huntsville is so strong that there\'s less than a months supply of housing inventory listed for sale today, which is the lowest the housing supply has been in Huntsville over the past 22 years. The city has an occupancy rate of 97%, and vacancies are filled in an average of 27 days.","historical":[{"Appreciation":3.12,"Rent":-7.33,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":4.28,"Rent":-1.83,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":4.79,"Rent":18.69,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":6.73,"Rent":-2.06,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":15.93,"Rent":31.65,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"huntsville_alabama","name":"Huntsville, Alabama","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/huntsville-al","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/huntsville-al","text":"Historical rental returns for 3 bedroom properties taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/12014/huntsville-al/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/12014/huntsville-al/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"jenner":{"description":"Jenner, California, is a small coastal town where the Russian River meets the Pacific Ocean. Known for its stunning ocean views, rugged cliffs, and peaceful atmosphere, it attracts nature lovers, kayakers, and hikers exploring nearby Sonoma Coast State Park. Wildlife, including harbor seals and migratory birds, thrives in this scenic area. With its growing popularity as a getaway destination, Jenner has also become an attractive spot for Airbnb investments. Vacation rentals range from cozy cottages to luxury oceanfront homes, drawing visitors seeking a tranquil retreat. Investors are drawn to the town\'s high demand for short-term rentals, particularly during peak travel seasons. Limited commercial development and strict zoning regulations help maintain its unspoiled charm, making it a desirable yet exclusive market.","historical":[{"Appreciation":5.1,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":1.9,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":-3.6,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":4.6,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":15.1,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":-1.6,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":0.9,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":1.4,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"jenner","name":"Jenner, California","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/98210/bodega-bay-ca-95450/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/98210/bodega-bay-ca-95450/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"joshua_tree":{"description":"Joshua Tree is famous for its unique desert landscapes and the iconic Joshua Tree National Park, which draws visitors for hiking, rock climbing, and incredible stargazing opportunities thanks to its clear night skies. Popular activities include exploring trails like Hidden Valley and Barker Dam, viewing art at the Noah Purifoy Outdoor Desert Museum, and enjoying live music and dining at Pappy & Harriet\'s in nearby Pioneertown. The real estate market in Joshua Tree has seen significant growth as it becomes a favored destination for artists, outdoor enthusiasts, and those seeking vacation homes. Many properties are designed to blend with the natural surroundings, offering desert views and eco-friendly architecture, and are frequently used for short-term rentals due to the area\'s rising tourism appeal.","historical":[{"Appreciation":-2.9,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":45.4,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":15,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":3.7,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":26.8,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":50.45,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":8.2,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":-10.9,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"joshua_tree","name":"Joshua Tree, California","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/96757/twentynine-palms-ca-92252/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/96757/twentynine-palms-ca-92252/","text":"Historical appreciation returns for Single Family Homes taken from"}]},"kansas_city":{"description":"Kansas City is the largest city in the state of Missouri and is known for its pro sports teams, delicious barbeque, and jazz music. The city has seen its population increase by 10.5% over the last decade and job postings in Kansas City are at record highs, while unemployment is down to just 2.4%. Average rents and appreciation in Kansas City have both increased by over 10% in just the last year, and KC is known as being one of the top markets for renters, as renter-occupied households in Kansas City make up 45% of the total occupied housing units.","historical":[{"Appreciation":10.08,"Rent":8.42,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":9.92,"Rent":13.26,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":8.33,"Rent":6.76,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":3.2,"Rent":-2.14,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":13.04,"Rent":10.2,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"kansas_city","name":"Kansas City, Missouri","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/kansas-city-mo","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/kansas-city-mo","text":"Historical rental returns for 3 bedroom properties taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/kansas-city-mo/home-values/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/kansas-city-mo/home-values/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"killington":{"description":"The Killington, Vermont area is the perfect place to get away from it all no matter what season it is. There are tons of outdoor activities including skiing, snowboarding, hiking, antiquing, golf, swimming, shopping, sightseeing, mountain biking and many more. This property is located less than 2 miles to the slopes and even closer to the bars and restaurants. Two golf courses are within 10 minutes of the house. The town recreation center is just a short distance away and features a swimming pool, soccer field, tennis courts, baseball diamond and playground. You\'ll also find plenty of trails, ponds, lakes, swimming holes and quaint Vermont towns a short drive away.","historical":[{"Appreciation":1.6,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":9.4,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":3.4,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":5.7,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":19,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":32.7,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":14.3,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":5.3,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"killington","name":"Killington, Vermont","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/92959/lubbock-tx-79416/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/92959/lubbock-tx-79416/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"knoxville":{"description":"Knoxville, Tennessee, blends Appalachian charm with modern vitality. Nestled near the Great Smoky Mountains, it offers easy access to hiking, waterfalls, and scenic drives. Downtown Knoxville buzzes with activity\u2014Market Square is the heart of it all, with live music, local shops, and farm-to-table restaurants. The city\'s arts scene thrives through the Knoxville Museum of Art and events like the Dogwood Arts Festival. University of Tennessee brings SEC energy to fall Saturdays, while the Tennessee River provides kayaking, paddleboarding, and waterfront dining. Neighborhoods like Old North Knoxville and South Knoxville (SoKno) mix historic homes with trendy breweries, climbing gyms, and bike trails like the Urban Wilderness. Foodies can explore everything from Southern comfort food to innovative cuisine, and music lovers can catch bluegrass, indie rock, and everything in between. With small-town warmth and a growing creative culture, Knoxville is one of Tennessee\'s best-kept secrets\u2014and a place people are proud to call home.","historical":[{"Appreciation":6.8,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":9.1,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":6.8,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":15.5,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":19.7,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":18.6,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":12.3,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":3.6,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"knoxville","name":"Knoxville, Tennessee","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/74550/knoxville-tn-37912/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/74550/knoxville-tn-37912/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"las_cruces":{"description":"Las Cruces, New Mexico, is the second-largest city in the state, located in the southern part of New Mexico. It serves as the county seat of Do\xf1a Ana County and is known for its rich cultural heritage, vibrant arts scene, and diverse economy. The city is surrounded by stunning landscapes, including the Organ Mountains and the Chihuahuan Desert, providing breathtaking views and outdoor recreation opportunities. Residents can enjoy hiking, biking, rock climbing, and camping. The nearby Organ Mountains-Desert Peaks National Monument is a popular destination for nature enthusiasts.","historical":[{"Appreciation":1,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":1.7,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":9,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":3.7,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":11.7,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":14.8,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":16.1,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"las_cruces","name":"Las Cruces, New Mexico","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/95505/las-cruces-nm-88001/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/95505/las-cruces-nm-88001/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"lawrence":{"description":"Living in Lawrence, Kansas offers a blend of cultural richness, academic opportunities, and community spirit. The city boasts a lively arts scene, numerous galleries, theaters, and live music venues. Home to the University of Kansas, it provides strong educational opportunities and a youthful atmosphere. Lawrence is community-oriented with frequent events and festivals, a vibrant downtown, and a rich history highlighted by the Watkins Museum of History. Outdoor enthusiasts can enjoy parks, trails, and activities like hiking and kayaking. With an affordable cost of living, diverse dining options, quality healthcare, and a focus on sustainability, Lawrence combines the charm of a smaller city with the convenience of proximity to Kansas City and Topeka.","historical":[{"Appreciation":4,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":9.3,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":8.2,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":7.2,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":8.2,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":20.3,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":2.5,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":2.6,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"lawrence","name":"Lawrence, Kansas","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/87059/lawrence-ks-66044/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/87059/lawrence-ks-66044/","text":"Historical appreciation returns for Condo / coop taken from"}]},"lehigh_acres":{"description":"Lehigh Acres, Florida offers a laid-back lifestyle with a strong sense of community and plenty of natural beauty. One of its best features is the affordability\u2014it\'s one of the more budget-friendly places to live in Southwest Florida, making it attractive for families, retirees, and first-time homebuyers. The area is known for its spacious lots and quiet residential neighborhoods. Nature lovers enjoy the abundance of green space, including parks, lakes, and golf courses, as well as easy access to nearby beaches and nature preserves. It\'s also conveniently located near Fort Myers, giving residents access to more urban amenities while still enjoying a peaceful, suburban atmosphere. Lehigh Acres is growing steadily, with new developments, schools, and small businesses adding to its appeal. The year-round sunshine and warm weather top it off, making it a great place for outdoor activities and a relaxed Florida lifestyle.","historical":[{"Appreciation":8.5,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":8.2,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":2.7,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":9.3,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":29.2,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":21.3,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":9.6,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":-2.3,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"lehigh_acres","name":"Lehigh Acres, Florida","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/399584/lehigh-acres-fl-33974/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/399584/lehigh-acres-fl-33974/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"little_rock":{"description":"Little Rock, Arkansas, offers a dynamic blend of southern charm and metropolitan amenities. The city is experiencing steady economic growth, driven by sectors such as healthcare, education, and technology. With its affordable cost of living, high quality of life, and a robust rental market, Little Rock presents a promising environment for real estate investment. The city\'s strategic location and ongoing urban development projects further enhance its appeal to investors seeking stable and profitable opportunities.","id":"little_rock","name":"Little Rock, Arkansas"},"louisville":{"description":"Nicknamed the \u201cBourbon City\u201d and \u201cGateway to the South\u201d, Louisville is located in north Kentucky and borders the Ohio River and Jefferson County in Indiana. As the largest city in the state, Louisville has a low cost of living and an active economy of public and private industry sectors including high tech, manufacturing, and transportation and shipping.  Realtor.com products that Louisville will outperform other real estate markets in 2022. According to the forecast, home prices in Louisville are predicted to rise by 4.5% while sales volume is expected to grow by 7.3%, compared to the U.S. average of 2.9% and 6.6% respectively. Over just the past year, rental rates in Louisville have increased by 12% with single-family homes accounting for the majority of housing units in the metro region.","historical":[{"Appreciation":7.38,"Rent":0.83,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":6.8,"Rent":3.2,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":4.12,"Rent":4.17,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":5.19,"Rent":9.12,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":9.12,"Rent":-0.07,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"louisville","name":"Louisville, Kentucky","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/louisville-ky","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/louisville-ky","text":"Historical rental returns for 3 bedroom properties taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/12455/louisville-ky/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/12455/louisville-ky/","text":"Historical appreciation returns for Single Family Homes taken from"}]},"lubbock":{"description":"Lubbock\'s resilient economy makes it an ideal location for real estate investment. Known for its stability, the city was one of the few markets that withstood the 2008 real estate downturn without a significant drop in real estate values. Key economic drivers include: \\n- Texas Tech University: A major educational institution attracting students, staff, and faculty.\\n- Medical Hub: Lubbock serves as a critical medical center for West Texas, ensuring a steady demand for housing.\\n- Agricultural Heritage: The city\'s strong roots in agriculture and cotton farming provide additional economic stability.","historical":[{"Appreciation":10.1,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":9.1,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":2,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":-3.9,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":8.4,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":14.2,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":10.3,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":-0.4,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"lubbock","name":"Lubbock, Texas","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/92959/lubbock-tx-79416/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/92959/lubbock-tx-79416/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"macon_georgia":{"description":"Macon, Georgia, truly shines with its rich history, vibrant culture, and southern charm. It stands as a musical mecca\u2014birthplace of legends like Little Richard, Otis Redding, and the Allman Brothers Band\u2014and honors its legacy through attractions like The Big House Museum and the revitalized Capricorn Sound Studios. Its ancient roots are showcased at Ocmulgee Mounds National Historical Park, where you can explore monumental Native American earthworks and enjoy scenic trails. Architectural elegance abounds at the \u201cPalace of the South\u201d\u2014the Hay House, a technological marvel of its time. Downtown, a walkable district brimming with history, artisan caf\xe9s, and lively festivals\u2014most notably the springtime Cherry Blossom Festival\u2014invites exploration. History buffs and sports fans won\u2019t want to miss the Tubman Museum or the Georgia Sports Hall of Fame. Together, Macon\u2019s music heritage, historical depth, and warm hospitality make it an unforgettable destination.","historical":[{"Appreciation":9.7,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":15.9,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":3.8,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":22.1,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":18,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":20.9,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":-0.8,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":8.4,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"macon_georgia","name":"Macon, Georgia","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/71471/macon-ga-31206/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/71471/macon-ga-31206/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"mccutchenville":{"description":"McCutchenville, Ohio, is the close-knit, peaceful community that defines small-town living. With a population under 200, everyone knows their neighbors, creating a deep sense of belonging and mutual support. Life moves at a slower, more intentional pace, far from the noise and rush of big cities. The surrounding countryside offers scenic views, open skies, and quiet roads, making it ideal for those who appreciate nature and solitude. There\'s also a strong connection to local history and tradition\u2014residents take pride in their roots, and community events, though modest, are heartfelt and bring everyone together. Located within driving distance of larger towns like Tiffin and Findlay, McCutchenville offers both tranquility and accessibility.","historical":[{"Appreciation":4.7,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":2.9,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":8.3,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":12.6,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":10.6,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":2.9,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":6.5,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":6.1,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"mccutchenville","name":"McCutchenville, Ohio","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/77353/mccutchenville-oh-44844/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/72059/miramar-beach-fl-32550/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"memphis":{"description":"Memphis is one of the most popular real estate investment markets both for cash flow and appreciation\u2013\u2013both rents and home prices have increased by over 12.5% in just the past year. The median age in Memphis is just 36.7 years, younger than both the state and national population. This is largely due to an influx of millennials moving from tier one markets, like San Francisco and New York, to less expensive markets like Memphis over the past year because of the ability to work remotely.\\n\\n Memphis is the best single family home growth market according to [Attom Data](https://www.attomdata.com/news/market-trends/single-family-rental/attom-data-solutions-q1-2021-single-family-rental-market-report/). According to [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-16/memphis-sacramento-vegas-see-accelerating-job-growth-pace), Memphis has been the #1 metro area in the U.S. for job creation when compared to the average area employment rate over the past 10 years. Over 88% of the residents in Memphis hold a high school diploma or higher, while nearly 29% have a bachelor\'s degree or an advanced degree.","historical":[{"Appreciation":4.3,"Rent":0,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":9.4,"Rent":0.1,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":8.6,"Rent":5.7,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":7.6,"Rent":1.2,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":12.7,"Rent":13.1,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"memphis","name":"Memphis, Tennessee","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/memphis-tn","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/memphis-tn","text":"Historical rental returns taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/memphis-tn/home-values/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/memphis-tn/home-values/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"miami":{"description":"From pristine beaches and top rated attractions, to lavish hotels, eclectic dining and a thriving arts and culture scene, Miami is regarded as one of the top destination cities in the world. Miami has a population of over 6 million people, making it the ninth largest city in the United States. It has the third-largest skyline in the U.S., and is a major center and leader in finance, commerce, culture, arts, and international trade. A major transportation and business hub, Miami is a leading resort and Atlantic Ocean port situated on Biscayne Bay. In August 2022, Miami home prices were up 22.6% compared to last year, selling for a median price of $515K. On average, homes in Miami sell after 46 days on the market compared to 51 days last year.","historical":[{"Appreciation":5.59,"Rent":-0.3,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":2.27,"Rent":-2.04,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":3.98,"Rent":-2,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":0.41,"Rent":-5.33,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":6.26,"Rent":-8.23,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"miami","name":"Miami, Florida","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/miami-fl","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/miami-fl","text":"Historical rental returns for 2 bedroom properties taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/12700/miami-fl/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/12700/miami-fl/","text":"Historical appreciation returns taken from"}]},"milwaukee_wisconsin":{"description":"Milwaukee, Wisconsin, is a dynamic city on the shores of Lake Michigan, offering a mix of natural beauty and cultural vibrancy. Its scenic lakefront, parks, and bike trails make it ideal for outdoor enthusiasts, while its thriving arts scene, highlighted by the Milwaukee Art Museum and Summerfest, appeals to culture lovers. Known for its craft breweries, diverse dining options, and iconic foods like cheese curds, Milwaukee is a haven for foodies. The city\'s affordable cost of living and variety of housing options, from historic neighborhoods to modern apartments, make it an attractive place to settle. Milwaukee is also home to renowned universities and a growing startup ecosystem, fostering opportunities for education and innovation. With a strong sense of community and welcoming residents, the city balances big-city amenities with Midwestern charm, offering an appealing lifestyle for those seeking culture, affordability, and natural beauty.","historical":[{"Appreciation":3.9,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":11.8,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":17.4,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":10.4,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":20,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":17,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":12.9,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":8.2,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"milwaukee_wisconsin","name":"Milwaukee, Wisconsin","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/81304/milwaukee-wi-53224/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/81304/milwaukee-wi-53224/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"miramar_beach":{"description":"Miramar Beach, Florida, offers the perfect blend of coastal beauty and laid-back charm, making it a favorite destination for both residents and visitors. Located along the stunning Emerald Coast, it boasts sugar-white sand and crystal-clear turquoise waters ideal for swimming, sunbathing, and water sports. The beach is the heart of the community, but there\'s more than just shoreline\u2014Miramar Beach features upscale shopping, great dining, and a welcoming atmosphere. Scenic Gulf Drive offers breathtaking views and easy beach access, while nearby Destin provides additional entertainment and nightlife options. Residents enjoy a relaxed lifestyle with warm weather year-round, friendly neighbors, and a strong sense of community. Whether you\'re biking along the coastal paths, exploring local boutiques, or enjoying fresh seafood by the water, Miramar Beach combines natural beauty with convenience and comfort.","historical":[{"Appreciation":7.6,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":6.6,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":3.9,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":11.9,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":37.7,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":12.1,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":-0.3,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":-5,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"miramar_beach","name":"Miramar Beach, Florida","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/72059/miramar-beach-fl-32550/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/72059/miramar-beach-fl-32550/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"norwalk":{"description":"Norwalk is a city in Los Angeles County, California. Norwalk offers an exceptional quality of life with excellent schools, cultural attractions, and a strong job market. The median sale price in Norwalk in October, 2023 is $693,000, a 6% year-over-year increase. Safety is paramount in Norwalk. The city is known for its well-maintained neighborhoods and vigilant community policing, creating an environment where residents and visitors can feel secure. Peaceful streets, well-kept parks, and a strong sense of community contribute to a harmonious living experience.","historical":[{"Appreciation":7.65,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":14.11,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":11.58,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":3.2,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":11.5,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":18.85,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":0.92,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"norwalk","name":"Norwalk, California","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/96193/norwalk-ca-90650/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/96193/norwalk-ca-90650/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"ogden":{"description":"Ogden, Utah, is an attractive place to live due to its excellent outdoor recreation opportunities, including skiing, hiking, and mountain biking in the nearby Wasatch Mountains. The city offers an affordable cost of living and a rich historic charm, particularly evident on Historic 25th Street with its shops, restaurants, and galleries. Ogden fosters a strong sense of community through local events and festivals, and residents benefit from educational opportunities at Weber State University. Additionally, its proximity to Salt Lake City provides easy access to metropolitan amenities and job opportunities while enjoying the benefits of a smaller city.","historical":[{"Appreciation":10.1,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":11.8,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":12.9,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":9.3,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":17.8,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":25.8,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":2.4,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":1.8,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"ogden","name":"Ogden, Utah","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/94562/ogden-ut-84404/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/94562/ogden-ut-84404/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"palm_bay":{"description":"Palm Bay, Florida, combines natural beauty with growing urban development, making it an attractive place to live. Its highlights include Turkey Creek Sanctuary, a popular spot for hiking and wildlife viewing, as well as its close proximity to the beaches of Melbourne and the Atlantic Ocean. The area offers quiet, spacious suburban neighborhoods, perfect for those seeking a peaceful lifestyle. With increasing infrastructure, including new shops, restaurants, and healthcare facilities, Palm Bay provides both convenience and affordability. Additionally, its expanding business and economic opportunities make it a promising location for both families and professionals.","historical":[{"Appreciation":8.2,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":12,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":7.5,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":4.8,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":11.1,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":26.3,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":14,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":0.5,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"palm_bay","name":"Palm Bay, Florida","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/72296/palm-bay-fl-32908/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/72296/palm-bay-fl-32908/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"palm_coast":{"description":"In Palm Coast, the vibrant lifestyle harmonizes effortlessly with its natural environment. The city boasts numerous beautiful parks, a vast network of over 130 miles of interconnected trails and paths ideal for walking and biking, and abundant opportunities for fishing, boating, tennis, and golf. Positioned between the renowned destinations of St. Augustine and Daytona Beach, Palm Coast is home to world-class golf courses such as the Jack Nicklaus-designed Ocean Course at Hammock Beach Resort & Spa. Visitors can also enjoy picturesque beaches and explore the rich biodiversity of the area, spotting egrets, tortoises, and other wildlife along wooden boardwalks. Additionally, Central Park in Town Center serves as a beloved event venue, offering several acres of open space at the heart of Palm Coast\'s vibrant downtown area.","historical":[{"Appreciation":6.6,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":6.3,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":5.1,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":4.5,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":8.9,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":29.9,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":8.9,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"palm_coast","name":"Palm Coast, Florida","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/71816/palm-coast-fl-32137/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/71816/palm-coast-fl-32137/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"peoria":{"description":"Peoria, Arizona, offers a blend of outdoor adventures, cultural experiences, and family-friendly attractions. Lake Pleasant Regional Park is a highlight, providing opportunities for boating, fishing, hiking, and camping amid scenic desert landscapes. Sports enthusiasts can enjoy spring training games at the Peoria Sports Complex, the seasonal home of the San Diego Padres and Seattle Mariners. The P83 Entertainment District features diverse dining, shopping, and entertainment options, making it a lively spot for visitors. Historic Old Town Peoria showcases the city\'s heritage with charming storefronts, local eateries, and public art. For performing arts lovers, the Arizona Broadway Theatre offers Broadway-style productions coupled with dining experiences. Additionally, the Peoria Center for the Performing Arts hosts various theatrical performances, enriching the city\'s cultural scene.","historical":[{"Appreciation":6.1,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":6.8,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":5.5,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":14.5,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":29.2,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":3.1,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":0.4,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":-0.3,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"peoria","name":"Peoria, Arizona","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/94956/peoria-az-85382/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/94956/peoria-az-85382/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"pigeon_forge":{"description":"Pigeon Forge, Tennessee, nestled in the Smoky Mountains, is a vibrant destination known for its mix of natural beauty and family-friendly attractions. One of its biggest draws is Dollywood, a world-class theme park offering thrilling rides, live music, and Appalachian culture. The nearby Great Smoky Mountains National Park provides endless outdoor adventures like hiking, scenic drives, and wildlife viewing. The Island in Pigeon Forge is another popular spot, featuring shopping, dining, and the iconic Great Smoky Mountain Wheel. For a taste of Southern charm, visitors enjoy dinner shows like Dolly Parton\'s Stampede and Pirates Voyage. The area also boasts unique museums, including the Titanic Museum and Alcatraz East. Whether you\'re seeking adventure, entertainment, or relaxation, Pigeon Forge combines rustic charm with modern fun, making it a top vacation choice for families, couples, and nature lovers alike.","id":"pigeon_forge","name":"Pigeon Forge, Tennessee"},"pittsburgh":{"description":"Pittsburgh is a renown US city with abundant shopping areas, nice restaurants, and outstanding views of the Monongahela, Allegheny, and Ohio Rivers. It is the second largest city in Pennsylvania and is home to three major sports teams: The Pittsburgh Pirates, Penguins, and Steelers. Pittsburgh has many of the factors that real estate investors look for, including activity in the rental market, quality of life, and affordability. Those are a few of the reasons why renter-occupied households account for 50% of the total occupied housing units in Pittsburgh. Over the last five years home values in Pittsburgh have increased by more than 63% and the GDP of Pittsburgh has increased more than 31% over the past 10 years, taking it to more than $153.3 billion.","historical":[{"Appreciation":5.75,"Rent":1.09,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":7.48,"Rent":13.21,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":8.86,"Rent":2.82,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":5.23,"Rent":-7.13,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":12.15,"Rent":7.73,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"pittsburgh","name":"Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/pittsburgh-pa","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/pittsburgh-pa","text":"Historical rental returns for 4 bedroom homes taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/pittsburg-pa/home-values/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/pittsburg-pa/home-values/","text":"Historical appreciation returns for all homes taken from"}]},"portland":{"description":"Portland, Oregon is a vibrant and scenic city in the USA\'s Pacific Northwest and is famous for greenery, microbreweries, coffeehouses and food trucks. The city is home to around 653,000 people. As the largest city in the state, it\'s famed for its huge expanses of green space, from parks and forests to breathtaking mountaintops. Portland has a hot job market, a high quality of life, and access to lots of natural areas.","historical":[{"Appreciation":9.79,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":4.09,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":3.64,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":2.84,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":9.17,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":17.15,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":4.52,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"portland","name":"Portland, Oregon","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/99138/tigard-or-97224/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/99138/tigard-or-97224/","text":"Historical appreciation returns taken from"}]},"quad_cities":{"description":"The Quad Cities is a region of cities in the U.S. states of Iowa and Illinois: Davenport and Bettendorf in southeastern Iowa, and Rock Island, Moline and East Moline in northwestern Illinois. It is a well-known real estate investment market known for its excellent living, affordable real estate, strong schools, a low cost of living, easy access to neighboring cities, and amenities for every want or interest. The U.S. News & World Report ranks the Quad Cities as the sixth most affordable place to live in the country in 2020-2021. The Quad Cities is home to Fortune 500 company Deere & Company. There are 150 other companies on Fortune 500 and 1000 lists that have a presence in the region, as well as the Rock Island Arsenal, a major military installation.","historical":[],"id":"quad_cities","name":"Quad Cities, Iowa - Illinois","sources":[]},"saint_albans":{"description":"Saint Albans, Missouri, is a scenic and serene community known for its natural beauty and luxury living. The best aspects include its picturesque landscapes, with rolling hills, forests, and views of the Missouri River. It\'s a haven for outdoor enthusiasts, offering excellent hiking, biking, and golfing, especially at the prestigious Saint Albans Country Club. The area is also known for its peaceful, small-town charm, yet it\'s conveniently close to St. Louis, providing a balance of tranquility and access to urban amenities. The community is tight-knit, with a focus on privacy and exclusivity, making it an attractive location for those seeking a refined lifestyle.","historical":[{"Appreciation":-0.1,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":3.6,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":3.2,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":6.5,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":10.1,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":15.7,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":3.4,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":1.6,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"saint_albans","name":"Saint Albans, Missouri","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/85907/labadie-mo-63073/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/85907/labadie-mo-63073/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"san_antonio":{"description":"Quiet, tucked away in Central San Antonio, the neighborhood of Castle Hills was established in the 60\'s & 70\'s and features custom-built, mid-century modern, ranch style mini-mansions. The neighborhood\'s low traffic, extra-wide streets, and mature trees allow for enjoyable walks or bike rides, especially at sunrise/sunset. San Antonio, as a whole, offers a unique blend of history, culture, and modern amenities, making it an appealing place to live. The downtown area, with attractions like the River Walk, the Alamo, and the lively Pearl District, draws both residents and visitors. Alamo Heights and Stone Oak provide top-rated schools, beautiful parks, and shopping destinations, while Southtown is known for its artistic flair, galleries, and vibrant dining scene. The city\'s warm climate and access to outdoor spaces, including nearby state parks and the Texas Hill Country, encourage an active lifestyle. San Antonio also hosts many cultural events and festivals, reflecting its rich heritage and diverse community.","historical":[{"Appreciation":5.54,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":10,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":5.5,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":5.3,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":9,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":10.2,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":8.5,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":-2.6,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"san_antonio","name":"San Antonio, Texas","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/92309/san-antonio-tx-78213/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/92309/san-antonio-tx-78213/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"san_francisco":{"description":"San Francisco\'s Lower Haight neighborhood, where Toronado Pub is located, offers a vibrant mix of culture, history, and local charm. Nestled between the bustling Haight-Ashbury and the lively Mission District, this area blends Victorian architecture with a laid-back, artistic vibe. The streets are lined with colorful murals, cozy cafes, and eclectic shops, making it perfect for wandering. Nearby Duboce Park provides green space for dogs and sunseekers, while the N-Judah Muni line offers quick access to downtown and the beach. Just a short walk away, you\'ll find the iconic Painted Ladies and Alamo Square, offering postcard views of the city. The area also boasts easy access to Golden Gate Park and Buena Vista Park for nature lovers. With a diverse community, great transit, and a mix of old-school character and modern energy, the Lower Haight is one of San Francisco\'s most underrated but rewarding neighborhoods to explore.","historical":[{"Appreciation":5.3,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":3.3,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":2.7,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":-1.4,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":7.8,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":-10.2,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":-5.7,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":0.5,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"san_francisco","name":"San Francisco, California","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/97571/san-francisco-ca-94117/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/97571/san-francisco-ca-94117/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"scottsdale":{"description":"Scottsdale, Arizona, offers an exceptional quality of life with over 300 days of sunshine annually and comfortably mild winters. This vibrant city is a paradise for outdoor enthusiasts, providing numerous opportunities for hiking, biking, and golfing amidst breathtaking desert landscapes. Scottsdale is renowned for its excellent healthcare, top-rated schools, and a flourishing arts scene, featuring galleries, museums, and cultural events. The city boasts a diverse culinary scene and upscale shopping, including the renowned Scottsdale Fashion Square. Safety is a key advantage, with low crime rates contributing to a secure living environment. The robust economy presents ample job opportunities, particularly in sectors like technology, healthcare, and tourism. Additionally, Scottsdale\'s proximity to Phoenix offers the perks of a larger city while maintaining a relaxed suburban atmosphere. With its blend of natural beauty, cultural richness, and economic vitality, Scottsdale stands out as an ideal place to call home.","historical":[{"Appreciation":2.4,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":9.1,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":6.6,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":7.3,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":14,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":25.5,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":10.3,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":0.6,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"scottsdale","name":"Scottsdale, Arizona","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/94846/phoenix-az-85254/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/94846/phoenix-az-85254/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"shelby_michigan":{"description":"Shelby, Michigan offers small-town charm and easy access to the beauty of Lake Michigan. A short drive west leads to Silver Lake Sand Dunes, perfect for dune rides, hiking, or enjoying panoramic views. The area\'s pristine beaches invite swimming, sunbathing, and stunning sunsets, while the historic Little Sable Point Lighthouse offers insight into Michigan\'s maritime history. Surrounded by rolling orchards and farmland, Shelby is known for its fresh, local produce, showcased at farmers\' markets, especially during cherry and apple seasons. Outdoor enthusiasts will love the Hart-Montague Trail State Park, a scenic route ideal for biking or walking through picturesque countryside. Whether exploring the dunes, relaxing by the lake, or savoring the region\'s natural bounty, Shelby provides a peaceful escape with a perfect mix of adventure and tranquility.","historical":[{"Appreciation":0.9,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":10,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":4,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":5.4,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":10.1,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":23.2,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":5.6,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":0.9,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"shelby_michigan","name":"Shelby, Michigan","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/79767/shelby-mi-49455/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/79767/shelby-mi-49455/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"shoreline":{"description":"Shoreline, Washington is a vibrant suburban city located just north of Seattle, offering a perfect blend of urban convenience and natural beauty. Known for its tree-lined streets and strong community vibe, Shoreline is an ideal place for families, students, and outdoor enthusiasts. One of its biggest draws is the easy access to Puget Sound, with parks like Richmond Beach Saltwater Park providing stunning views, walking trails, and beach access. The Interurban Trail offers great biking and jogging opportunities, connecting neighborhoods through a scenic route. Shoreline is also home to excellent schools and Shoreline Community College, contributing to its reputation as an education-friendly city. The area maintains a peaceful, residential feel while still offering plenty of shopping, dining, and entertainment options. With quick access to Seattle via I-5 and Highway 99, Shoreline offers the best of both worlds: calm, suburban life with proximity to a bustling urban center.","historical":[{"Appreciation":18,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":4.2,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":-0.4,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":13,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":12.2,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":2.6,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":1.3,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":6.8,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"shoreline","name":"Shoreline, Washington","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/99589/seattle-wa-98133/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/99589/seattle-wa-98133/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"st_louis":{"description":"St Louis is one of the most sought after markets for rental properties in the United States, with more than half of the properties in the city being occupied by renters. The city has seen an influx of millennials moving in as the tech and creative sectors continue to grow. So much so that the millennial generation now outweighs the baby boomers generation.\\n\\n Over the past 5 years, the average home price in St. Louis has increased by almost 30% and the average rents have increased by over 35%. [Forbes](https://www.forbes.com/places/mo/st-louis/) ranked St. Louis as one of the best places for business and careers last year, due to the fact that high-tech employment in the city grew by 2.2%. St. Louis is touted as a biotech and business center and is home to almost 40 colleges throughout the city. St. Louis pro sports teams include the St. Louis Cardinals and the St. Louis Blues hockey team.","historical":[{"Appreciation":6.97,"Rent":11.36,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":6.18,"Rent":1,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":7.17,"Rent":17.82,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":3.94,"Rent":0.67,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":3.25,"Rent":4.51,"years":"2020-2021"}],"id":"st_louis","name":"St Louis, Missouri","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/st-louis-mo","linkText":"https://www.zumper.com/rent-research/st-louis-mo","text":"Historical rental returns for 2 bedroom properties taken from"},{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/stlouis-mi/home-values/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/stlouis-mi/home-values/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"the_dalles":{"description":"The Dalles, Oregon, is a historic city along the Columbia River, known for its natural beauty and outdoor activities. Highlights include the Columbia Gorge Discovery Center, which offers insights into the region\'s history, and The Dalles Dam, an engineering marvel with great views. Downtown The Dalles has a charming, small-town atmosphere with unique shops and historic buildings. The Dalles Mountain Ranch offers stunning views and wildflower hikes, while Sunshine Mill Winery provides a unique experience in a repurposed flour mill. For a taste of local culture, visit the Fort Dalles Museum or explore the cherry orchards in the area.","historical":[{"Appreciation":8.4,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":14.4,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":11.8,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":9.7,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":14.8,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":17.6,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":3.6,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":1,"years":"2023-2024"}],"id":"the_dalles","name":"The Dalles, Oregon","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/99058/the-dalles-or-97058/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/99058/the-dalles-or-97058/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"tiffin":{"description":"Tiffin, Ohio, offers a charming blend of small-town warmth and vibrant community life. The historic downtown is rich with unique shops, local eateries, and beautiful architecture, creating a welcoming atmosphere. Tiffin University and Heidelberg University infuse the town with educational and cultural opportunities, hosting events, lectures, and sports. Outdoor enthusiasts enjoy the scenic beauty of Hedges-Boyer Park and the Sandusky River, perfect for walking, fishing, and picnicking. The cost of living is affordable, making it an attractive place for families and retirees. Tiffin\'s sense of community shines through in its local festivals, farmers markets, and family-friendly events. The revitalized downtown area has brought new businesses and entertainment options while preserving its historic charm. Friendly neighbors, good schools, and a slower pace of life make Tiffin a comfortable, close-knit community.","historical":[{"Appreciation":5.6,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":4.2,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":2.7,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":14.2,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":10.4,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":4.5,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":5.3,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":4.4,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"tiffin","name":"Tiffin, Ohio","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/77382/tiffin-oh-44883/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/77382/tiffin-oh-44883/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"tulum":{"description":"Tulum is one of the most desired jewels of the Riviera Maya, located in the middle of the jungle with beautiful white sand beaches, palm trees, turquoise blue sea, spectacular lagoons, cenotes, rivers, underwater caverns and an impressive Mayan archaeological site on the seashore, which was used as an astrological ceremonial center, make Tulum a unique destination in the Mexican Caribbean. The construction of the city of Tulum was based on the concept of the \u201cfour corners\u201d which refers to the cardinal points and which in turn arises from the ancient cosmic pattern of five points. The city as a quadrilateral represented an ordered, rational world, made for gods and men alike.","historical":[{"Appreciation":7.8,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":7.5,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":8.1,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":10.8,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":7.5,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":12.1,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":14.6,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"tulum","name":"Tulum, Mexico"},"waianae":{"description":"Waianae is a beautiful coastal community located on the leeward side of Oahu, Hawaii. Known for its stunning landscapes, Waianae is surrounded by dramatic mountain ranges and boasts some of the island\'s most pristine beaches, including the serene Makaha Beach. This area offers a more laid-back, rural atmosphere compared to the bustling urban areas of Honolulu. Waianae is home to a vibrant Native Hawaiian community and a rich cultural heritage, with many residents deeply connected to the land and traditions. The region is also renowned for outdoor activities, such as hiking, fishing, and snorkeling, with the crystal-clear waters and abundant marine life offering incredible opportunities for nature enthusiasts. While the area is known for its natural beauty, Waianae also faces challenges related to poverty and infrastructure, but the resilience and close-knit community spirit of its residents remain its greatest strength.","historical":[{"Appreciation":10.35,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":3.2,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":4.3,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":9.7,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":16,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":2.2,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":2,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":-1.8,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"waianae","name":"Waianae, Hawaii","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/98926/waianae-hi-96792/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/98926/waianae-hi-96792/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"watervliet":{"description":"Nestled within the Capital District of New York, Watervliet offers a blend of historical significance and modern charm. Known for its Dutch heritage dating back to the 17th century, the city\'s name, meaning \'water marsh\', reflects its location along the Hudson and Mohawk rivers. Watervliet is notably home to the longstanding Watervliet Arsenal, a historic military manufacturing center dating back to the early 19th century. This small city of around 10,000 residents boasts a diverse community and a rich tapestry of historic sites, including the venerable St. Patrick\'s Church. With its proximity to Albany and scenic waterways, Watervliet provides a gateway to exploring both local history and the natural beauty of the region.","historical":[{"Appreciation":1.5,"years":"2016-2017"},{"Appreciation":4.5,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":5.1,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":3.1,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":6.9,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":9.2,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":6.3,"years":"2022-2023"}],"id":"watervliet","name":"Watervliet, New York","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/62462/watervliet-ny-12189/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/62462/watervliet-ny-12189/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]},"wawarsing_new_york":{"description":"Wawarsing, New York, nestled in Ulster County, offers a picturesque setting where the Catskill Mountains meet the Shawangunk Ridge. The town is known for its natural beauty, with access to Minnewaska State Park, Sam\'s Point Preserve, and the scenic Rondout Reservoir. Residents enjoy a blend of rural charm and outdoor activities, including hiking, biking, fishing, and rock climbing. Living in Wawarsing provides a tranquil lifestyle with a strong sense of community. The town\'s affordability, proximity to nature, and convenient access to nearby hubs like Kingston and New Paltz make it an attractive choice for families, retirees, and outdoor enthusiasts. Local attractions include the Napanoch Point Lookout, historic sites like the D&H Canal Museum, and seasonal farmers\' markets. Its serene environment, combined with recreational opportunities and a small-town feel, makes Wawarsing a delightful place to live and explore.","id":"wawarsing_new_york","name":"Wawarsing, New York"},"worcester":{"description":"What makes Worcester, Massachusetts truly stand out is its perfect balance of history, culture, and momentum. As New England\'s second-largest city, it combines small-city charm with big-city amenities. The arts thrive here\u2014whether it\'s world-class exhibits at the Worcester Art Museum or live performances at The Hanover Theatre. Food lovers will find everything from old-school diners to global cuisine, reflecting the city\'s rich diversity. Worcester is also a center of innovation, powered by top-tier institutions like WPI and UMass Medical School, and a growing startup ecosystem. Its central location offers quick access to Boston and the rest of New England, yet Worcester remains proudly self-contained. Parks like Elm Park and the Cascades offer green escapes within city limits. With a deep sense of community, an affordable lifestyle, and a downtown in the midst of exciting revitalization, Worcester is quickly becoming one of Massachusetts\' most compelling places to live and grow.","historical":[{"Appreciation":8,"years":"2017-2018"},{"Appreciation":6.3,"years":"2018-2019"},{"Appreciation":7.4,"years":"2019-2020"},{"Appreciation":15.8,"years":"2020-2021"},{"Appreciation":11.6,"years":"2021-2022"},{"Appreciation":7.7,"years":"2022-2023"},{"Appreciation":9.4,"years":"2023-2024"},{"Appreciation":5.3,"years":"2024-2025"}],"id":"worcester","name":"Worcester, Massachusetts","sources":[{"link":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/58444/worcester-ma-01605/","linkText":"https://www.zillow.com/home-values/58444/worcester-ma-01605/","text":"Historical appreciation returns (Single family) taken from"}]}}')},89308(e){"use strict";e.exports=JSON.parse('{"AD":{"name":"Andorra","native":"Andorra","phone":"376","continent":"EU","capital":"Andorra la Vella","currency":"EUR","languages":["ca"],"emoji":"\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\udde9","emojiU":"U+1F1E6 U+1F1E9"},"AE":{"name":"United Arab Emirates","native":"\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u062d\u062f\u0629","phone":"971","continent":"AS","capital":"Abu Dhabi","currency":"AED","languages":["ar"],"emoji":"\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddea","emojiU":"U+1F1E6 U+1F1EA"},"AF":{"name":"Afghanistan","native":"\u0627\u0641\u063a\u0627\u0646\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646","phone":"93","continent":"AS","capital":"Kabul","currency":"AFN","languages":["ps","uz","tk"],"emoji":"\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddeb","emojiU":"U+1F1E6 U+1F1EB"},"AG":{"name":"Antigua and Barbuda","native":"Antigua and Barbuda","phone":"1268","continent":"NA","capital":"Saint John\'s","currency":"XCD","languages":["en"],"emoji":"\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddec","emojiU":"U+1F1E6 U+1F1EC"},"AI":{"name":"Anguilla","native":"Anguilla","phone":"1264","continent":"NA","capital":"The Valley","currency":"XCD","languages":["en"],"emoji":"\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddee","emojiU":"U+1F1E6 U+1F1EE"},"AL":{"name":"Albania","native":"Shqip\xebria","phone":"355","continent":"EU","capital":"Tirana","currency":"ALL","languages":["sq"],"emoji":"\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddf1","emojiU":"U+1F1E6 U+1F1F1"},"AM":{"name":"Armenia","native":"\u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576","phone":"374","continent":"AS","capital":"Yerevan","currency":"AMD","languages":["hy","ru"],"emoji":"\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddf2","emojiU":"U+1F1E6 U+1F1F2"},"AO":{"name":"Angola","native":"Angola"